                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d81">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.04/12313: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-04T23:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 4, 1938—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 4—6:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>99. Mr. Hugh Wilson<note n="3" xml:id="d81fn3">Newly appointed Ambassador to
                        Germany.</note> informs me that, when talking privately with Mr. Eden for a
                    moment this afternoon, Mr. Eden told him that if the Japanese attacked Hong Kong
                    they would act at once in its defense; that this might mean the withdrawal of
                    substantial forces from the Mediterranean but that the British could not do
                    otherwise. He further said that the British would act to defend Hong Kong if
                    attacked regardless of what American action might be.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
